  "slides": [
    {
      "slideId": 1,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Understanding Backup & Recovery"
        },
        {
          "type": "definition",
          "value": "Backup is creating copies of important files or systems so they can be restored if deleted, corrupted, or lost. Recovery is the process of restoring this data back to a working state."
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "Linux provides multiple tools to back up files, directories, databases, and entire systems. Good backup strategy protects you against accidental deletion, power failure, viruses, or system crashes."
        },
        {
          "type": "table",
          "value": [
            ["Backup Type", "Explanation"],
            ["Full Backup", "Complete copy of data (largest & safest)"],
            ["Incremental Backup", "Copies only changed files since last backup"],
            ["Differential Backup", "Copies changes since last full backup"],
            ["Local Backup", "Stored on same system or drive"],
            ["Remote Backup", "Stored on external server/cloud"]
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "Golden Rule: 3 copies → 2 storage types → 1 offsite (3-2-1 backup rule)"
        }
      ]
    },


    {
      "slideId": 2,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Backup Tools in Linux"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "We can back up files using cp, tar, rsync, or mysqldump (for databases) depending on the situation."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "cp -r /home/user/documents /backup/",
          "description": "Simple directory backup (local copy)"
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "tar -czf backup.tar.gz /home/user/documents",
          "description": "Archive & compress backup folder"
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "rsync -avz /home/user/ user@192.168.1.10:/remote-backup/",
          "description": "Remote incremental backup over SSH"
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "mysqldump -u root -p school > school_backup.sql",
          "description": "Backup a MySQL/MariaDB database"
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "Use rsync for regular backups; tar for packaged archives; mysqldump for databases."
        }
      ],
      "video": null
    },


    {
      "slideId": 3,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Restoring Files & Databases"
        },
        {
          "type": "stepByStep",
          "steps": [
            "Locate the backup source file or archive",
            "Choose restore destination (where data will go)",
            "Verify space, permissions, and users before restoring",
            "Restore files or databases using correct commands"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "tar -xzf backup.tar.gz -C /restore-location",
          "description": "Restore from tar archive"
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "rsync -avz user@192.168.1.10:/remote-backup/ /home/user/restore/",
          "description": "Restore from remote backup"
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "mysql -u root -p school < school_backup.sql",
          "description": "Restore MySQL database from SQL backup"
        },
        {
          "type": "table",
          "value": [
            ["Restore Check", "Why It Matters"],
            ["Disk Space", "Avoid half-restored backups"],
            ["Permissions", "Some files need sudo to write"],
            ["Database User Exists", "Must exist before restoring DB"],
            ["Firewall/SSH Access", "Needed for remote backup restore"]
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "Always test restore on a safe test location before replacing real data."
        }
      ],
      "video": null
    },


